docs.abstract: The bill, which would expand checks to almost all firearms sales, is almost certain to pass the House but faces long odds in the Republican-controlled Senate.
docs.snippet: The bill, which would expand checks to almost all firearms sales, is almost certain to pass the House but faces long odds in the Republican-controlled Senate.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Emboldened House Democrats, seeking a politically charged debate on gun control, unveiled legislation on Tuesday to expand background checks to nearly all firearms purchases, a move timed to mark the eighth anniversary of the mass shooting in Arizona that nearly killed former Representative Gabrielle Giffords.

headline.main: Background Check Bill Marks Gun Control as a Priority for House Democrats
headline.print_headline: Bill on Background Checks Shows Gun Control Is Priority for Democrats

docs.abstract: The Treasury secretary will speak in a classified session about his plan to end sanctions on companies controlled by Oleg Deripaska, a Kremlin ally.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Democrats have summoned Steven Mnuchin, the Treasury secretary, to Congress on Thursday to deliver a classified briefing about the Trump administration’s plans to end sanctions on companies linked to the billionaire Russian oligarch Oleg V. Deripaska.

headline.main: Congress Summons Mnuchin to Explain Russian Sanctions Removal
headline.print_headline: Mnuchin to Explain End of Sanctions

docs.abstract: After two years of pining, Democrats finally have the gavels and subpoenas they need to investigate President Trump and his administration. Blockbuster findings? Don’t expect them anytime soon.
docs.snippet: After two years of pining, Democrats finally have the gavels and subpoenas they need to investigate President Trump and his administration. Blockbuster findings? Don’t expect them anytime soon.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democrats, transitioning into the House majority, have quietly sent dozens of letters in recent weeks seeking documents and testimony from President Trump’s businesses, his campaign and his administration, setting the table for investigations that could reach the center of his presidency.

headline.main: Democrats Start Investigative Gears, but Slowly
headline.print_headline: House Democrats’ Investigative Wheels Begin to Turn

docs.abstract: The Senate first blocked Mr. Trump’s proposal to add $5.7 billion for his border wall to legislation to resume funding for the government, then turned back a Democratic measure that omitted the wall.
docs.snippet: The Senate first blocked Mr. Trump’s proposal to add $5.7 billion for his border wall to legislation to resume funding for the government, then turned back a Democratic measure that omitted the wall.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A pair of measures to reopen the government — one with President Trump’s border wall, the other without it — failed in the Senate on Thursday, sending lawmakers from both parties into frenzied efforts to forge a compromise that could end the nearly six-week partial shutdown.

headline.main: Collapse of Two Plans to End Shutdown Propels Urgent Negotiations
headline.print_headline: Senate Bills Fail, Raising Urgency of Impasse Talks

docs.abstract: The White House doubled its estimate of the shutdown’s drag on growth, and other economists warned a long stalemate could push the economy into a contraction.
docs.snippet: The White House doubled its estimate of the shutdown’s drag on growth, and other economists warned a long stalemate could push the economy into a contraction.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The partial government shutdown is inflicting far greater damage on the United States economy than previously estimated, the White House acknowledged on Tuesday, as President Trump’s economists doubled projections of how much economic growth is being lost each week the standoff with Democrats continues.

headline.main: Shutdown’s Economic Damage Starts to Pile Up, Threatening an End to Growth
headline.print_headline: Strain of Shutdown Is Spreading As Hot Economy Loses Its Steam

docs.snippet: Cliff Sims, a former communications staff member, portrays a West Wing full of back-stabbing and duplicity under President Trump in “Team of Vipers.”
docs.lead_paragraph: John F. Kelly, as White House chief of staff, presented himself as the man leading a charge of “country first, president second.” The attorney general suggested administering lie-detector tests to the small group of people with access to transcripts of the president’s calls with foreign leaders. And President Trump sought a list of “enemies” working in the White House communications shop.

docs.abstract: President Trump’s monthlong impasse with Congress over his proposed border wall has all but frozen the rest of his policy agenda.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For the last month, President Trump’s public schedule has mostly been a sparse document.
